HIGHER Education Students' Loan Board (HESLB) has attained 96 per cent of the loans repayment target for 2020/2021 fiscal year. HESLB Executive Director Mr Abdul-Razaq Badru revealed that here recently in an interview with the ‘Daily News’ on the status of loans disbursement and repayments. He attributed the achievements to increased efficiency which saw loans repayment increasing from 28.21bn/- in 2015/2016 to 183.66bn/- by the fiscal year 2020/2021. Mr Razaq said the amount collected is equivalent to 96 per cent of the target of collecting 190bn/- in 2020/2021 fiscal year despite the Covid-19 pandemic. "Over the past four years the government has continued to support the board to fulfill its two major responsibilities, which are providing higher education loans to the needy Tanzanian's youths and collecting loans repaid by the beneficiaries,” he explained. He further said that the government has continued to increase the budget for the HESLB from 450bn/- in 2019/2020 to 570bn/- in 2021/2022 noting that the increase has also helped to increase the number of beneficiaries. Mr Razaq   noted that following the increase in budget the number of beneficiaries has increased from 130,072 students in 2019/2020 to 176,617 students 2021/2022 academic year. For the ongoing fiscal year 2021/2022, he said a total of 98.02bn/- has been collected in the first half of the year from July- December 2021 which is equivalent to 107 percent of the target of t collecting a total of 91.2bn/- He said the improved loans collection mechanism and  loans delivery  services to students was due to various reasons including the government investment  in improving Information and Communication Technology system which has simplified the release and repayment of loans. He noted that currently the beneficiary student receives loans within 24 hours through biometric system and thus reducing complaints of loans delays. “We have now improved auditing exercise to employers to identify beneficiaries who have not yet paid their loans and start repaying their loans back as per the boards’ laws," he said, adding that the board is also running various campaign aimed at educating students on the proper use of the loans and the importance of repaying them back.